e =\n| notableworks =\n}}\n\n'''[[Dornford Yates]]''' was the pseudonym of the English novelist '''Cecil William Mercer''' (7 August 1885 \u2013 5 March 1960), whose novels and short stories, some humorous (the ''Berry'' books), some [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]]s (the ''Chandos'' books), were best-sellers in the period between the First and Second World Wars.\n\nThe categorization of Yates's novels is based on the list that appears opposite the title page of his last published work, ''B-Berry And I Look Back''.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Yates |first=Dornford |title=''B-Berry And I Look Back'' |publisher=[[Ward Lock & Co]] |year=1958 |at=Opposite title page}}</ref> All works are full-length novels except where noted. Not included are the uncollected short stories.\n{{clear}}\n\n== The Berry books ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|+\nThe Berry Books\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year of first<br />publication\n! scope=\"col\" | First edition publisher<br />\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" |{{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''The Brother of Daphne''\n| 1914\n|[[Ward Lock & Co]]\n| Short stories, originally published in ''[[The Windsor Magazine]]''<ref name =\"SmithersAppx\">{{Cite book|at=Appendix I |title=Dornford Yates |last= Smithers |first=AJ |publisher=[[Hodder & Stoughton|Hodder and Stoughton]] |year=1982 |location=London |isbn=0 340 27547 2}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref name=\"BLcat003995523\">{{Cite web |url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=003995523&con_lng=eng |title=British Library details for item 003995523  |website=primocat.bl.uk |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''The Courts of Idleness''\n| 1920\n|[[Ward Lock & Co]]\n|Short stories, originally published in ''[[The Windsor Magazine]]''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |<ref name=\"BLcat003995525\">{{Cite web